### The Key Idea

Dynamic programming solves problems by breaking them into ==overlapping subproblems== and storing their solutions. Unlike divide-and-conquer, DP reuses previously computed results.

## Fibonacci Numbers

The naive recursive approach has exponential time complexity:

$$
T(n) = T(n-1) + T(n-2) + O(1)
$$

This gives $T(n) = O(2^n)$.

### Memoized Version

```python
def fib(n, memo={}):
    if n in memo:
        return memo[n]
    if n <= 1:
        return n
    memo[n] = fib(n - 1, memo) + fib(n - 2, memo)
    return memo[n]
```

Time complexity: $O(n)$. Space complexity: $O(n)$.

### Bottom-Up Version

```python
def fib(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return n
    dp = [0] * (n + 1)
    dp[1] = 1
    for i in range(2, n + 1):
        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2]
    return dp[n]
```

## The Knapsack Problem

Given $n$ items with weights $w_1, \ldots, w_n$ and values $v_1, \ldots, v_n$, and a capacity $W$, maximize the total value without exceeding the weight limit.

### Recurrence

$$
OPT(i, w) = \max(OPT(i-1, w), v_i + OPT(i-1, w - w_i))
$$

### Complexity

| Variant | Time | Space |
| --- | :---: | :---: |
| 0/1 Knapsack | $O(nW)$ | $O(nW)$ |
| Unbounded Knapsack | $O(nW)$ | $O(W)$ |
| Fractional Knapsack | $O(n \log n)$ | $O(1)$ |

N> The 0/1 knapsack is *pseudo-polynomial* because $W$ is exponential in the number of bits needed to represent it.

